==English==

===Etymology===
Via {{etyl|enm}} {{term|oncle|lang=enm}} and {{etyl|fro}} {{term|oncle|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|avunculus||mother’s brother”, literally “little grandfather|lang=la}}, the diminutive of {{term|avus||grandfather|lang=la}}, from the {{proto|Indo-European|awo-|grandfather, adult male relative other than one's father}}
: this word replaced the Old English {{term|eam||maternal uncle|lang=ang}} / {{term|fædera||paternal uncle|lang=ang}}, which represents the Germanic form of the same root.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|ŭngʹkəl}}, {{IPA|/ˈʌŋ.kəl/}}, {{SAMPA|/"VN.k@l/}}
*: {{audio|en-us-uncle.ogg|Audio (US)}}
